```python
# Tool returns a result that DECLARES its associated UI
def show_dashboard(params):
    return {
        "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Dashboard ready"}],
        "_meta": {
            "ui": {
                "resourceUri": "ui://dashboard/sales",        # the HTML app resource
                "csp": "default-src 'self'; script-src 'self'",  # content security policy
                "permissions": [],                              # no extra permissions
            }
        }
    }
# The ui:// resource (served via resources/read) returns the HTML app
# with MIME text/html;profile=mcp-app
```
```javascript
// Inside the sandboxed iframe app: talk to the host via postMessage + JSON-RPC
window.parent.postMessage({
    jsonrpc: "2.0", id: 1, method: "tools/call",
    params: { name: "get_sales_data", arguments: { quarter: "Q4" } }
}, "*");
window.addEventListener("message", (e) => {
    const resp = e.data;        // JSON-RPC response from the host
    if (resp.id === 1) renderChart(resp.result);
});
```

**Declaring the UI metadata:** a tool result includes **`_meta.ui`** to declare its associated app:
- **`_meta.ui.resourceUri`** — points to the **`ui://` resource** containing the HTML app (the host fetches it via `resources/read`).
- **`_meta.ui.csp`** — a **Content-Security-Policy** the host applies to the app's iframe — restricting what the app can load/execute (e.g. only same-origin scripts, no inline scripts, no external network) to **limit what malicious HTML could do**.
- **`_meta.ui.permissions`** — declares **what capabilities the app needs** (camera, clipboard, etc.) — the host enforces a **permissions-policy**, granting only the declared (and user-approved) capabilities. Default: **none** (least privilege).
These let the host **render the app under a tightly-scoped security profile** rather than as unrestricted HTML.

**The iframe-sandbox postMessage JSON-RPC:** the app runs in a **sandboxed iframe** and **can't directly call MCP** — it communicates with the host via the browser's **`postMessage`** API, carrying **JSON-RPC messages** (Lesson 6's wire format, now host↔app). The app **posts a JSON-RPC request** (e.g. 'call tool get_sales_data') to the host (`window.parent`), the **host validates and executes it** (mediating — it doesn't blindly trust the app), and **posts the JSON-RPC response back** via a `message` event. So the app can **call tools, fetch data, and update** — interactively — but **always through the host as a mediator** (the host decides what the app is allowed to do). This is the bridge that makes the UI *interactive* (it can drive tool calls) while keeping the host in control.

**Why the app is sandboxed in an iframe:** the HTML app is **server-provided — i.e. untrusted** (a third-party MCP server is now rendering code in the user's host). Letting **arbitrary server HTML/JS run with full access** to the host would be a **massive security hole** — it could **steal data, make unauthorized requests, escape to the host page, run drive-by attacks, or abuse the user's session**. So the host **renders it in a sandboxed iframe** with:
- **iframe `sandbox` attribute** (no top-navigation, no same-origin escape, restricted scripts),
- **CSP** (limit script/network sources — no exfiltration),
- **permissions-policy** (no camera/clipboard/etc. unless declared+approved),
- **postMessage-only communication** (the app can't touch the host directly — every interaction goes through the mediated JSON-RPC channel the host controls).
The sandbox is what makes **'let a server render HTML in your agent'** acceptably safe — it **confines** the untrusted app so it can be interactive but can't harm the host or exfiltrate data. The whole MCP Apps design is **'rich interactivity within a tight sandbox'** — and getting the sandbox right (CSP, permissions, mediated postMessage) is the core safety challenge (next exercise).
